content.description: This is a cool face climb with some very interesting rock. It might be a tad harder, because a hold broke off when I was climbing. Climb lots of face moves and a ledge to the anchor.
content.location: On the farthest left of the crag, it is a lone sport climb with anchors 30’ up.

content.description: There is a common anchor between two cracks. The left is thin and wavy, and the right is a perfect corner crack to a small roof at the top.
content.protection: Single rack from fingers to 3 inches.
content.location: These are the first routes on the right side of the wall.

content.description: Sport climb to the right of the other. This is face climbing on good sandstone.

content.description: Stem up to the crack, fist to hand size. The crack ends halfway up the route, I believe, and there's a lot of loose stuff afterwards. Stem or chimney to the top.

content.description: Climb a hand to fist crack to an anchor.

climbs.name: Choss Pile Far Left (AKA Gorilla Gripper’s Corpse)
climbs.fa: I believe this was the FA: Mike Cichon, Sarah Zubrin, 4/25/21

content.description:
This is the crack climbing next to the

5.9 sport route

. Climb through the choss, and traverse to the anchor on the

sport route

. A hold broke off, so it might be harder. Gear can be placed in the seam next to it as well as in the crack. Use runners, and belay far away from the base. This appears to be the remnants of Gorilla Gripper? I am not sure.

This is a crazy hand/fist crack that could use some cleaning up. Build an anchor with some smaller pieces. The crux is getting through the overhanging bulge to the east scramble finish. Walk off the top to the climber’s right.
content.location: The start is located at the far right side of the crag. There is a very distinct rock at the base. See the photo.
